## Objective

Modify the `submit()` method in `QuestionPrompt`'s imperative handle so that pressing Enter advances to the next question on non-last questions, and only actually submits on the last question. This creates a natural sequential flow.

## Current Code

In `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/QuestionPrompt.tsx`, the imperative handle's `submit` method (around line 194):

```typescript
submit() {
  handleSubmit();
},
```

## New Code

```typescript
submit() {
  const currentIdx = Number(activeTab);
  if (currentIdx < questions.length - 1) {
    // Advance to next question
    setActiveTab(String(currentIdx + 1));
    return;
  }
  // On last question: actually submit
  handleSubmit();
},
```

This keeps the submit logic self-contained in QuestionPrompt. The `useToolShortcuts` hook in ChatPanel calls `handle.submit()` on Enter — no changes needed there.

## Edge Cases

- **Single question**: `currentIdx` (0) is not `< questions.length - 1` (0), so it falls through to `handleSubmit()`. Correct.
- **Last question in multi-question**: Same logic. Correct.
- **Middle question**: Advances without submitting. The user can still go back via Back button or Left arrow.
- **Incomplete question**: The submit advance happens regardless of whether the current question has an answer. This is intentional — the user can navigate freely and the Submit button on the last question checks `isComplete()` before actually submitting.

## Files Changed

- `apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/QuestionPrompt.tsx` — Modify submit() in imperative handle

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Enter key on a non-last question advances to the next question
- [ ] Enter key on the last question calls `handleSubmit()` (actual submission)
- [ ] Single-question prompts submit directly on Enter (no advancement)
- [ ] The `useToolShortcuts` hook requires no changes
- [ ] `pnpm typecheck` passes

